post_text: Sobering thoughts. It‚Äôs important to remember.
shared_text:
Create-abilities
September 10 at 4:15 PM ¬∑

‚ÄúOn this day... 19 years ago 246 people went to sleep in preparation for their morning flights. 2,606 people went to sleep in preparation for work in the morning. 343 firefighters went to sleep in preparation for their morning shift. 60 police officers went to sleep in preparation for morning patrol. 8 paramedics went to sleep in preparation for the morning shift. None of them saw past 10:00am Sept 11, 2001. In one single moment life may never be the same. As you live and enjoy the breaths you take today and tonight before you go to sleep in preparation for your life tomorrow, kiss the ones you love, snuggle a little tighter, and never take one second of your life for granted.‚Äù

üíõ

#wewillneverforget

post_text: We are SO proud of all our students who have been working so hard to help our neighbors in Louisiana.
shared_text:
Bay High School - Panama City, FL
September 10 at 10:46 AM ¬∑

Here is a message from a member of the community affected by Hurricane Laura. We are so proud of the team from Bay High School who traveled to provide disaster relief!

"I am a proud Cameron Parish resident, and I was passing out meals and supplies at Grand Lake High School this past weekend. I personally want to thank your school for gathering and delivering much needed items for Cameron Parish. The team that delivered the items had amazing smiles on their faces and were a pleasure to meet! I will speak for all residents of Cameron Parish by thanking your guys so very much for items that were very much needed! Our Parish has been blessed by so many people, like your school, that went out of their way to help us! Thank you again and may God bless you all!!!"

post_text: What a great reminder for all of us. We value our military neighbors and thank them, and those in all branches, for their service to our country.
shared_text:
Naval Surface Warfare Center Panama City Division
September 1 at 2:27 PM ¬∑

75 years ago today, September 1, 1945, the then U.S. Navy Mine Countermeasures Station was commissioned. Today, and for the month of September, we are celebrating 75 years of the U.S. Navy in Panama City, Florida.

Beginning with a small cadre of military and civilian personnel focusing on mine countermeasures, the NSWC PCD has grown to over 1,550 people supporting a variety of missions in the littoral battlespace for the Navy and Marine Corps.

#NSWCPCD #WarfightingDominance #LittoralBattlespace #PCD75 #HIstory #WarfareCenters #NHHC Naval Sea Systems Command #NavyLab

We will be having a ‚ÄúCaravan Volunteer‚Äù meeting for those leaving to drop off supplies on Monday, August 31st at 5:30 in the Tommy Oliver parking lot. We plan on leaving the morning of Friday, September 4th.

Additionally, please do not donate expired food, old toys, or used clothing. We must respect our fellow neighbors as we help. üôÇ Thanks so much!

Bay High family and friends:

In the aftermath of a disaster like Hurricane Michael, the people of Panama City know all too well that survivors need immediate assistance. Natural disasters take precious life, do massive damage, and leave behind unimaginable destruction.

With Louisiana and Texas in the storm‚Äôs crosshairs, Bay High is asking for a call to arms‚Äî if you are able to donate any of the listed items, PLEASE do so!

Supplies can be dropped off at Bay High School from 8am-2pm CST until Friday, September 4th at 2pm. These items will be delivered to those in need. Should you have any questions, please reach out to Nathaniel Taylor at taylonc@bay.k12.fl.us.

Panama City Quality of Life
August 24 at 11:56 AM ¬∑

Attention PC Teens!!
Want to help the City of Panama City design parks that you and your friends would love? Then become a teen park designer in a FREE two-day workshop (Sept 12 & 19). Create a model of your design and present it to the Panama City Commission on September 22. The workshops will be held on two Saturdays and you will work with other teens as well as urban planners, architects, and Panama City park staff to create the designs. ArchforKids will teach you how to plan and build your models. The Panama City Quality of Life Department will provide breakfast and lunch on Sept 12 and 19. Transportation is available if needed. Seats are limited. #ArchAcademy

Register now at https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/PCTEEN

RUMOR CONTROL: We are aware of a FB post circulating (that began in England actually) saying that schools have the right to take children away from their parents if they have Covid. THIS IS RIDICULOUS, FALSE INFORMATION DESIGNED TO ALARM AND SCARE PEOPLE. There is no such act in the United States, schools are NOT usurping parental rights and this is all FALSE. Please do your part in checking out FB posts before sharing them. There‚Äôs enough in this pandemic to be concerned about without fake posts adding hysteria ... we feel terrible that anyone may have seen and believed this nonsense. You can always count on our page for reliable, trustworthy, up-to-date information about our schools.
https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/kids-covid-quarantine/

96 Cases of 16oz bottles of hand sanitizer (2,304 individual bottles)
96 Case of 1 Gallon bottles of liquid hand sanitizer (384 Gallons)
32 Cases of 300ml bottles of hand sanitizer (1120 individual bottles)
42 Cases of single use paper masks face masks (84,000 Masks)

(132,000 total individual masks)

post_text: Revised calendar for 2020-2021 just approved by the School Board. Please note that the union and district worked together to revise the calendar based upon the delayed start date. We were able to convert 3 of the 4 PLC Days to school days, adjust a couple of other holidays and still maintain the breaks at Thanksgiving and Spring Break that we know are so important to our families. We also managed to keep close to the same ending date which, we know, is also important to our parents. It's not possible to please everyone with a calendar but many people worked very hard on this, in a very short time, to ensure most of our collective priorities were addressed.

post_text:
An Update from the Superintendent. You can go here to make your selection: https://focus.bayschools.net/focus/, scroll down on the home page of your parent portal account to the section called 2020 back-to-school options. There's a video there that walks you through the next steps.
If you attempted to make a selection on Parent Portal but do not see the Child Info screen stated in the directions please continue to read:
Your student may not be attached to your Parent Portal account. To correct this, please call your child's school and they will attach them to you after verifying custody. This is a quick process and you can make your selection right after this is done.
Alternatively, you may have a Limited parent account due to custody arrangements. In this case, you will not be able to make a selection for your student. An account with full custody and parent access will need to make the selection instead. Please contact your child's school to verify if this is the case and make corrections, if appropriate

post_text: We join our Ram friends and family in mourning the unexpected loss of Ms. Alvis.
shared_text:
Principal Pilson (Ram 1)
July 18 at 3:17 PM ¬∑

It is with the heaviest of hearts that I share this information. Early this morning Ms. Jennifer Alvis passed away unexpectedly. She will be remembered as a true Ram. She loved Rutherford High School. She taught regular, AP, and IB courses. She planned everything from school dances to blood drives. Students and staff universally love her. I will remember her fondly for her unwavering support of Rutherford and my leadership. She leaves behind a husband and 3 sons all Rams. Two of which are to graduate next week. I will share funeral arrangements and ways to support the family once I get them. Until then the family has asked that friends share fond memories of Ms. Alvis. Feel free to put them in the comment section. Ms. Alvis we love you and will miss you. Rest in peace and love my dear friend.

post_text: We join our A. Crawford Mosley High School Family in mourning the loss of the iconic Mr. Jordan.
shared_text:
A. Crawford Mosley High School
July 14 at 9:31 AM ¬∑

The Mosley family was saddened to hear of the recent passing of the great Bob Jordan. Mr. Jordan was a founding member of A. Crawford Mosley High School and was instrumental in creating the Dolphin lifestyle that we know today. If you ask alumni, most fondly remember Mr. Jordan‚Äôs infamous intercom slogan: ‚ÄúPlease report to the Side Door.‚Äù After 43 years in education, Mr. Jordan retired from Mosley administration in 1997, but continued to visit his colleagues and family at the school he loved. He would even be called upon to fill in for administration when the need arose. Mosley High School is forever in debt to the contributions of Mr. Jordan, and we ask that you keep his family in your thoughts and prayers. The class of 1987 said it best: ‚ÄúMr. Jordan didn‚Äôt have to report to the side door; no doubt he went straight through the pearly gates.‚Äù

Update from DCF regarding the P-EBT cards: Please direct all P-EBT inquiries to the Florida Department of Children and Families (DCF) at 1-833-311-0321. DCF is the lead agency and will resolve all P-EBT issues regarding eligibility and distribution of P-EBT benefits.

If parents contact the district or schools directly, please let them know that DCF will handle all communication with parents that believe there was an error in the eligibility or issuance of P-EBT benefits. If the parent believes their child is eligible and DCF does not have their information in the P-EBT database, DCF will take their information, research the case and communicate the outcome to the parent.

post_text: Just wanted to update everyone regarding the Launchpad login issues. Currently Florida LambdaRail (FLR) is down due to a "break" in the line. FLR is the fiber optic network connection that we use to authenticate logins to our active directory and which allows us to log into Launchpad and other online resources. Our MIS dept has been working diligently with FLR, Classlink, and other vendors. FLR is scheduled to be back up over the weekend and we should have full access once FLR is back online.

It‚Äôs been wonderful to have had free meals at school since the hurricane and we appreciate the USDA for approving us for free meals again for 2020-21. Since the pandemic, ChartwellsK12 has been amazing and with their support we‚Äôve delivered more than 700,000 meals to date. Additionally, our partnership with Mercy Chefs is putting pop-up pantries at five locations a week to help get additional food to our families. It‚Äôs a HUGE project that works because many, many people are determined to make it happen for our kids and we‚Äôre grateful for all of them and for your continued support. http://www.epaperedition.com/Olive/ODN/Panama/shared/ShowArticle.aspx?doc=NEWSHERALD%2F2020%2F06%2F21&entity=Ar03701&sk=9B5C4E02&mode=text

post_text: Parents, we know you have questions and we do as well. Here‚Äôs what‚Äôs been released thus far from the Governor‚Äôs Office. Our community-based task forces have been working for the past month and their ideas/suggestions/proposals will be presented to the School Board at a workshop on July 14th. If you‚Äôre unable to attend, the event will be live-streamed (we will post the link ahead of time) and we will post all of the documents to our COVID-19 webpage. AFTER the workshop, when plans have been discussed, we will be sending out another stakeholder survey to all parents, guardians, employees and others in the community to get your feedback about what you‚Äôd like to see when schools reopen and what your concerns are currently. We‚Äôve already accomplished so much together since the storm, no doubt we can tackle this pandemic together as well. Please follow us on social media and check your email for regular updates via PeachJar. We appreciate your patience, concern and feedback as we plan together!

Bay County Sheriff's Office
June 4 at 9:45 AM ¬∑

FOOD DISTRIBUTION TODAY AT PC MALL!

Due to an unforeseen delay in loading this morning at the Farm Share warehouse, the truck is scheduled to arrive back in Bay County just before 11:30. There will be a slight delay in distribution.

PLEASE BE PATIENT AS WE ORGANIZE THE FOOD TO DISTRIBUTE!

Again, no registration is needed to receive the food. First come, first served!

Food distribution by the BCSO, Farm Share, ALL local law enforcement agencies, the Lead Coalition, the Bay County Interdenominational Ministry Alliance, and the Northwest Florida Minority Business Chamber of Commerce.

Despite the delay, we will have enough for 700 families. We appreciate your patience as we work fast to hand out the food.

post_text: Congratulations to Alex Robb of Surfside Middle School! Alex placed 2nd in Innovation World's "Ready, Set, Innovate" Competition for creating the Goofy Golf Grabber. We are so proud of you Alex!

post_text: We are pleased to announce that we have served over 605,000 meals to our community during this challenging time. As previously announced, this service will continue throughout the summer with a few changes. Beginning June 2, buses will deliver meals on Tuesday and Thursday. To find the bus stop closest to you, please go to www.bay.k12.fl.us and click on the Covid-19 update button. Then select Meals and choose the elementary school closest to you. The stops will be displayed and you can locate the one most convenient for you.

May 26, 2020

The Bay County Sheriff‚Äôs Office will conduct another food distribution in partnership with Farm Share. The distribution will be held this Thursday, May 28, 2020, at the Callaway Recreational Complex off of Hwy 22 in Callaway.

###

Prepared by R. Corley

Approved by Sheriff T. Ford

post_text: All of our high schools are working on different ways to ensure those entering military service have a chance to "graduate" before they go. We, as a community and as a district, thank these young men and women for their service.
shared_text:
A. Crawford Mosley High School Yearbook: Poseidon
May 20 at 3:58 PM ¬∑

This morning two of our Dolphins, Diamond St Pierre and Richard Lambert, participated in the first round of graduation recognition ceremonies for our students who will be involved in basic training for their branch of military service. These young people will not be able to attend the formal graduation ceremony with the rest of their class in July. These gentleman will be heading off to Army boot camp within the next two weeks. We are SO proud of you guys!

post_text: Sometimes you have to move backwards to move forwards and such is the case at Rutherford High School today. We're sad, but relieved, to see the old gym coming down finally because that will make way for a new facility. You may remember that Rutherford's old gym was heavily damaged as a result of the hurricane and we've been trying to get it demolished for some time now!

post_text: Parents, please read!
shared_text:
Panama City Police Department
May 12 at 11:41 AM ¬∑

In recent weeks, the Panama City Police Department has seized approximately 240 grams, $24,000 street value, of manufactured methamphetamine pills that resemble candy. The pills are multi-colored and have different emblems printed on them related to cartoon characters and superheroes. With the pills appearing to be kid-friendly and the danger stimulants pose if ingested by children, parents should stay alert and attentive to anything similar found in your child‚Äôs possession. If you notice any changes in your child‚Äôs behavior contact a medical provider. If you find items matching those depicted below, contact your local law enforcement agency.

Although the methamphetamine pills appear to be kid-friendly, it is more likely the pills are designed to evade law enforcement detection.

If you have information in reference to this case, please contact the Panama City Police Department, 850-872-3100, or you can report your tips anonymously via smartphone by downloading the ‚ÄúPanama City PD‚Äù Tip411 app in the Apple App Store or Google Play Store.
